It is characteristic of Cic. to gibe at the want of Greek scholarship shown by the Roman Epicureans (cf. i 3, 6; ii 3, 7; iv 3, 7, etc.)‚ and there is a grim humour in selecting the coterie who laid such stress upon pleasures of the senses, as examples of persons deprived of pleasure (and wisdom) ‘at one entrance.’ Epi- curei nostri and Graeci, moreover‚ give a better point to omnes nos below.
